<ab><lb n="1"/>  <w lemma="εὐεπήκοος">εὐεπηκόῳ</w>  <persName type="divine"><name nymRef="#Ἀσκλήπιος">Ἀ<lb n="2" break="no"/>σκληπίῳ</name></persName>  <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Εὐγενία">Εὐγενί<lb n="3" break="no"/>α</name></persName>  <w lemma="εὐχή">εὐχὴν</w>  <w lemma="ἀνατίθημι">ἀνέθηκεν</w>  </ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To Asklepios who listens well: Eugenia dedicated (in payment of) a vow</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>One of a group of votive offerings dedicated to Asclepius: three reliefs, <ref type="inscription" n="1214" target="050112.xml"/> (=63.568), <ref type="inscription" n="1215" target="050117.xml"/> (=63.570), <ref type="inscription" n="1216" target="150240.xml"/> (=70.551), and a base, <ref type="inscription" n="1224" target="040113.xml"/> (=90.26); the three with provenance were found in or near the Baths of Hadrian.</p>
            <p>The cult title is quite common, and implies that the prayer had been answered; it was probably for a child rather than for cure of trouble in the breasts.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography" n="none">
            <p>Unpublished.</p>
         </div>
